Germany, year zero
The 8th of May always reminds me of the year 1945. Because the end of the war in Europe was truly a decisive moment in my life.
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our little street, in the western suburbs of Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was drawing to a close.
My father, a resister, would return from the Brandenburg prison.
I would no longer have to hide like after my liberation from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
It was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was the chaos.
The Nazis gone, the occupying powers had not yet set up an administration.
We looted the stores in the neighborhood. I still have a few volumes of romantic poetry recovered from a bookstore.
I was sixteen. The occupying forces were committing all sorts of excesses.
It was difficult to obtain food.
My father was transported directly from his prison to the center of Berlin, and tasked with setting up - from scratch - the city's energy supply office.
For a while, there was no electricity, no transportation, and no organized life.
Victory or liberation?
For the Germans, it was a delicate question, even though for our family it was undoubtedly a liberation in every sense of the word.
But for what purpose?
For what future?
"You must help," my mother said.
I offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the delivery of basic food supplies to some distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back at school.
I had a special card as a "victim of fascism," while others wore the Iron Cross awarded for late military service.
Some were refugees from the East, many had seen their homes destroyed by bombings, and almost all mourned the loss of loved ones.
However, this phase did not last.
It is practically incredible, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the "German economic miracle."
Or more precisely, the West German economic miracle.
The differences between the occupying powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and especially accompanied by a new form of oppression.
Concentration camps like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and prisoners.
However, after a brief period of non-fraternization, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled reinforcement of autonomy.
One year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years later, elections.
Democracy was no empty word and relied on German traditions.
Certainly.
It was also the beginning of the Cold War, and each wanted to consolidate "their" part of Germany.
But there are still lessons to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular merit being mentioned.
The first is economic, and related to the Marshall Plan.
It may be regrettable, but democracy certainly takes root more easily in an economic recovery context.
It requires, above all, initiative on the part of individuals who wish to bring an end to a period of hardship.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (such as those of Ludwig Erhard, father of the "social market economy" in Germany), but things are easier with an initial capital.
Where the importance of American support through the Marshall Plan lies.
In the same way, the European Union has helped the formerly communist countries and continues to accompany them in their journey.
The other lesson, of a moral nature, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials rendered the guilt of Nazi leaders indisputable.
However, Germany did not embark on its long journey by focusing on the past.
In fact, many have described the years after 1949 under Adenauer as a period of "restoration," because too many minor Nazi figures remained in their positions.
In a way, the country ignored its past to move forward into the future.
Years later, after establishing a market economy and political democracy, Germany faced its past with considerable success.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other wounded countries therefore cause confusion.
However, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first the novelty, then an attempt to confront the past.
In the end, it is a better method.
In Europe, May 8, 2005, is an occasion to look back at the past with sadness and anger, but also to turn toward the future, proud of the achievements of the last decades and thus filled with hope.
